The Ministry of Health on Saturday recorded
398 positive COVID-19 cases from a sample size of 2,745 tested in the last
24 hours, raising the positivity rate to 14.5 per cent. Of the cases, 365 are Kenyans while 33
are foreigners; 202 are females and 196 are males, while the youngest is a
one-year-old child and the oldest is 96 years old. Total confirmed positive cases are now
329,107, while cumulative tests so far conducted are at 3,720,078. The infections were recorded across the
country as follows: Nairobi 237, Kiambu 46, Kitui 23, Murang’a 15, Uasin Gishu
12, Mombasa 11, Kericho 9, Kilifi 8, Nakuru 7, Siaya 6, Kisumu 4, Garissa 3,
Kisii 3, Embu 2, Kwale 2, Tana River 2, Nyeri 2, Homa Bay, Kajiado, Kakamega,
Narok, Meru and Migori had one case each. Health Cabinet Secretary Mutahi Kagwe, in a
statement to newsrooms on Thursday, said 218 patients recovered from the
disease; 199 from the Home-Based and Isolation Care Program while 19 are from
health facilities countrywide. Total recoveries are now at 320,364. However, no patient succumbed to the
disease; therefore, the cumulative fatalities remain at 5,651. “There are 70 patients currently admitted in
our health facilities, while 3,022 are under the Home-Based Isolation and Care
program,” noted CS Kagwe. “One patient is in the Intensive Care Unit
(ICU) on supplemental oxygen while 10 are in the general wards on supplemental
oxygen. No patient is in the High Dependency Unit (HDU).” On the vaccination exercise, the CS
revealed that a total of 18,573,028 vaccines have been administered across
the country. Of these, 16,640,059 are doses
administered to the adult population (18 years and above) as of June 17, 2022. He further stated that 1,489,798 doses were
administered to those between 15 to 17 years; 39,704 are below 15 years but
above 12 years, while 403,467 are booster doses. He stated that the total number of vaccines
administered in the last 24 hours is 17,198 while the total number of people
fully vaccinated is 6,137.  “Proportion of adults fully vaccinated was
31.5%. The government is working towards vaccinating a targeted population of
27,246,033,” added Kagwe.